1
00:00:03,750 --> 00:00:05,375
-[boy sobbing]
-[crossing bell ringing]

2
00:00:05,458 --> 00:00:06,875
[train horn honks]

3
00:00:08,625 --> 00:00:10,250
Put a sock in it!

4
00:00:10,333 --> 00:00:11,833
You're crying like
it's the end of the world,

5
00:00:11,916 --> 00:00:13,166
you big baby!

6
00:00:13,250 --> 00:00:14,458
It's a skinned knee!

7
00:00:14,541 --> 00:00:15,541
I'm the one
who broke her ankle

8
00:00:15,625 --> 00:00:18,208
in a million, billion places,
so there!

9
00:00:18,291 --> 00:00:19,083
Uhh!

10
00:00:19,166 --> 00:00:20,541
It's your fault
for making me

11
00:00:20,625 --> 00:00:21,916
tumble down the hill.

12
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:24,625
I didn't wanna!
Stop, already!

13
00:00:24,708 --> 00:00:25,708
[sobbing]

14
00:00:25,791 --> 00:00:27,208
<i>I guess I should be thankful</i>

15
00:00:27,291 --> 00:00:29,250
<i>it's only your knee</i>
<i>that got hurt.</i>

16
00:00:29,333 --> 00:00:31,458
<i>If you'd fallen</i>
<i>on your hands or anything,</i>

17
00:00:31,541 --> 00:00:35,708
<i>I know for a fact your Mom</i>
<i>would eat both of us alive.</i>

18
00:00:35,791 --> 00:00:36,708
[groans]

19
00:00:36,791 --> 00:00:39,208
[sobbing]

20
00:00:39,291 --> 00:00:40,583
If you don't stop right now,

21
00:00:40,666 --> 00:00:43,208
I'm gonna cry, too!

22
00:00:43,291 --> 00:00:45,125
[both sobbing]

23
00:00:50,250 --> 00:00:52,208
["Hikaru Nara" playing]

24
00:01:03,791 --> 00:01:06,541
[singing in Japanese]

25
00:02:22,458 --> 00:02:24,458
KOUSEI: Here.
Uh, you can borrow these.

26
00:02:24,541 --> 00:02:26,708
I'll toss your uniform
in the dryer, okay?

27
00:02:26,791 --> 00:02:28,375
KAORI: Sounds good.

28
00:02:28,458 --> 00:02:30,125
Nobody home, huh?

29
00:02:30,208 --> 00:02:30,833
My Dad's away
on business a lot.

30
00:02:30,916 --> 00:02:33,375
It's usually just me.

31
00:02:35,750 --> 00:02:38,833
Wow. I feel all tiny
in this shirt.

32
00:02:38,916 --> 00:02:40,125
[chuckles]

33
00:02:40,208 --> 00:02:42,333
[footsteps pattering]

34
00:02:47,666 --> 00:02:49,000
[gasps]

35
00:02:52,791 --> 00:02:56,458
[footsteps pattering]

36
00:02:56,541 --> 00:02:57,916
So now that you're all dry,
want coffee?

37
00:02:58,000 --> 00:02:59,666
Or I could heat up
some milk.

38
00:02:59,750 --> 00:03:02,458
-[yells]
-[wails]

39
00:03:02,541 --> 00:03:03,375
Okay, no coffee!
Just calm down!

40
00:03:07,166 --> 00:03:07,291
Uh...

41
00:03:09,666 --> 00:03:11,541
Look at you.

42
00:03:13,666 --> 00:03:14,375
I'm sorry.

43
00:03:16,250 --> 00:03:18,041
I'm sorry.

44
00:03:18,125 --> 00:03:20,083
Poor thing.

45
00:03:20,166 --> 00:03:22,250
[crying]

46
00:03:22,333 --> 00:03:23,791
[shrieks]

47
00:03:23,875 --> 00:03:26,166
Wholesome playing starts
with a wholesome environment!

48
00:03:26,250 --> 00:03:29,000
This place
is dust-bunny central!

49
00:03:31,500 --> 00:03:33,250
Huh?

50
00:03:33,333 --> 00:03:34,708
Hey, I didn't know
the two of you were neighbors.

51
00:03:34,791 --> 00:03:37,000
-Not what it looks like!
-TSUBAKI:<i> It's Kaori...</i>

52
00:03:37,083 --> 00:03:38,000
<i>wearing Kousei's shirt,</i>

53
00:03:38,083 --> 00:03:40,125
<i>and her hair is wet?</i>

54
00:03:40,208 --> 00:03:41,500
Give me a chance!
[wails]

55
00:03:41,583 --> 00:03:42,750
-[growling]
-[whimpers]

56
00:03:43,166 --> 00:03:46,208
[roars]

57
00:03:49,291 --> 00:03:50,500
[growling]

58
00:03:51,541 --> 00:03:54,625
Tsubaki sure is fired up
this afternoon.

59
00:03:54,708 --> 00:03:55,875
Yeah, like a volcano.

60
00:03:55,958 --> 00:03:59,625
Somehow, I don't think
this is about softball.

61
00:03:59,708 --> 00:04:01,416
[panting]

62
00:04:01,500 --> 00:04:04,291
-[piano music playing]
-[gasps]

63
00:04:04,375 --> 00:04:06,958
[disjointed
classical music playing]

64
00:04:07,041 --> 00:04:08,750
[groans] You're kidding.

65
00:04:08,833 --> 00:04:09,875
That's what I sound like?

66
00:04:09,958 --> 00:04:11,500
Yup. I was recording

67
00:04:11,583 --> 00:04:13,708
while you were practicing
a second ago.

68
00:04:13,791 --> 00:04:15,458
Feast your ears
on Frédéric Chopin's

69
00:04:15,541 --> 00:04:18,333
"Etude Opus 25,
Number 5".

70
00:04:18,416 --> 00:04:20,083
That's not me! How could I
play it so off tempo?!

71
00:04:20,166 --> 00:04:22,625
There's gotta be
some mistake!

72
00:04:22,708 --> 00:04:24,208
-Wow, that is bad.
-No kidding.

73
00:04:24,291 --> 00:04:26,500
-TSUBAKI: Hmph!
-Eep!

74
00:04:26,583 --> 00:04:28,500
KOUSEI:<i> I can't compete</i>
<i>sounding like this.</i>

75
00:04:28,583 --> 00:04:31,041
<i>Good thing I haven't</i>
<i>sent in my application.</i>

76
00:04:31,125 --> 00:04:32,500
Your paperwork's
all taken care of.

77
00:04:32,583 --> 00:04:34,125
How did you
get my wallet?!

78
00:04:34,208 --> 00:04:35,166
So what's this competition
all about?

79
00:04:35,250 --> 00:04:36,708
She's a witch.
She's a witch.

80
00:04:36,791 --> 00:04:38,708
It's the Maihou
Music Competition.

81
00:04:38,791 --> 00:04:40,958
Students from all over Japan
take part.

82
00:04:41,041 --> 00:04:43,166
Doing well's
a really big deal.

83
00:04:43,250 --> 00:04:44,666
Win at the national level,

84
00:04:44,750 --> 00:04:47,583
and you might even
get to perform overseas.

85
00:04:47,666 --> 00:04:50,458
-Wow.
-That's awesome.

86
00:04:50,541 --> 00:04:52,416
TSUBAKI:<i> Hearing her talk</i>
<i>about that stuff,</i>

87
00:04:52,500 --> 00:04:54,458
<i>it's like a whole other world,</i>

88
00:04:54,541 --> 00:04:56,750
<i>one I can't even find on a map.</i>

89
00:04:56,833 --> 00:04:59,375
Why did I ever agree to this
in the first place?

90
00:04:59,458 --> 00:05:01,208
KAORI: Chin up, Friend A.
Let's rise to the occasion.

91
00:05:01,291 --> 00:05:03,541
You're gonna prove
you can play,

92
00:05:03,625 --> 00:05:04,875
even if you can't hear
a solitary note.

93
00:05:04,958 --> 00:05:07,208
-Whoa!
-Whoa!

94
00:05:07,291 --> 00:05:08,250
Don't you forget,
"It takes courage

95
00:05:08,333 --> 00:05:10,041
to sail
in uncharted waters!"

96
00:05:10,125 --> 00:05:12,000
-Hmph.
-Who said that?

97
00:05:12,083 --> 00:05:13,416
-Snoopy, duh.
-Huh?

98
00:05:13,500 --> 00:05:14,666
Ruff!

99
00:05:14,750 --> 00:05:16,958
-Picture it in your head.
-ALL: Mm-hmm.

100
00:05:17,041 --> 00:05:18,208
And here's another
nugget of wisdom for you.

101
00:05:18,291 --> 00:05:21,458
"Before your fingers
touch the keys,

102
00:05:21,541 --> 00:05:23,208
you must determine in your mind
how you're going to play it."

103
00:05:23,291 --> 00:05:25,416
Anton Rubenstein
said that, right?

104
00:05:25,500 --> 00:05:29,000
Why do you play piano
in the first place?

105
00:05:29,083 --> 00:05:31,291
Is it for you
or someone else?

106
00:05:31,375 --> 00:05:34,791
How do you want
to play this piece?

107
00:05:34,875 --> 00:05:36,291
No one can tell you how.

108
00:05:36,375 --> 00:05:37,750
It's your decision to make.

109
00:05:37,833 --> 00:05:38,333
[sighs]

110
00:05:40,958 --> 00:05:42,708
You and Chopin'll
figure it out.

111
00:05:42,791 --> 00:05:45,083
My work in this town is done.
Whoo-hoo!

112
00:05:45,166 --> 00:05:46,541
[both whooping]

113
00:05:46,625 --> 00:05:47,541
WATARI: Let's just
have class out here today!

114
00:05:47,625 --> 00:05:49,083
KASHIWAGI:
Hurry it up, Tsubaki.

115
00:05:49,166 --> 00:05:50,708
[growls] Dummy!

116
00:05:50,791 --> 00:05:52,583
[student chatter]

117
00:05:53,208 --> 00:05:55,250
KOUSEI:<i> Okay.</i>

118
00:05:55,333 --> 00:05:57,666
<i>Just you and me, huh?</i>

119
00:05:57,750 --> 00:05:58,916
<i>Let's get to work.</i>

120
00:06:00,791 --> 00:06:02,708
["Etude Opus 25,
Number 5" playing]

121
00:06:06,375 --> 00:06:08,083
Chopin?

122
00:06:08,166 --> 00:06:10,750
Don't tell me
that's Kousei.

123
00:06:10,833 --> 00:06:11,916
Mm-hmm.

124
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:15,250
Huh.
So he's playing again?

125
00:06:15,333 --> 00:06:17,125
Yeah.

126
00:06:17,208 --> 00:06:18,416
Maybe I should
bring him over a snack.

127
00:06:23,500 --> 00:06:24,458
[marker squeaks]

128
00:06:24,541 --> 00:06:26,000
What do you got?

129
00:06:26,083 --> 00:06:27,333
A horse-drawn carriage
over the cobblestones--

130
00:06:27,416 --> 00:06:28,875
Ugh!
Way to rock the clichés.

131
00:06:28,958 --> 00:06:29,875
[marker squeaks]

132
00:06:29,958 --> 00:06:32,125
What do you got?

133
00:06:32,208 --> 00:06:33,333
Sunny-side up eggs
for break--

134
00:06:33,416 --> 00:06:34,833
No! Stop thinking
with your stomach!

135
00:06:34,916 --> 00:06:35,916
[marker squeaks]

136
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:37,458
Imagine it.

137
00:06:37,541 --> 00:06:39,958
["Etude Opus 25,
Number 5" playing]

138
00:06:40,041 --> 00:06:41,791
KOUSEI:<i> Imagine it.</i>

139
00:06:41,875 --> 00:06:43,250
<i>Imagine it.</i>

140
00:06:43,333 --> 00:06:45,166
<i>Imagine it.</i>

141
00:06:46,708 --> 00:06:49,875
<i>That's great,</i>
<i>but what's it mean?</i>

142
00:06:49,958 --> 00:06:52,458
<i>I interpret the music</i>
<i>either way.</i>

143
00:06:52,541 --> 00:06:55,166
KAORI:<i> How do you</i>
<i>want to play this piece?</i>

144
00:06:57,375 --> 00:06:59,458
KOUSEI:
<i>How do I want to play...</i>

145
00:06:59,541 --> 00:07:01,291
<i>this piece.</i>

146
00:07:01,375 --> 00:07:02,166
[sighs]

147
00:07:02,250 --> 00:07:04,541
[student chatter outside]

148
00:07:04,625 --> 00:07:05,666
Eh?

149
00:07:05,750 --> 00:07:07,250
[sighing]

150
00:07:15,500 --> 00:07:16,541
[sighing]

151
00:07:20,750 --> 00:07:21,500
[murmurs]

152
00:07:23,916 --> 00:07:25,041
[chuckles]

153
00:07:26,166 --> 00:07:29,500
<i>She looks like an angel.</i>

154
00:07:29,583 --> 00:07:31,083
<i>She's not yelling, for once.</i>

155
00:07:31,166 --> 00:07:32,291
[murmurs]

156
00:07:46,125 --> 00:07:48,125
[playing
"Etude Opus 25, Number 5"]

157
00:07:52,333 --> 00:07:54,166
[music fades]

158
00:07:55,500 --> 00:07:57,208
[footsteps pattering]

159
00:07:57,291 --> 00:07:58,791
KAORI:
You ready for Regionals?

160
00:07:58,875 --> 00:08:00,333
TSUBAKI: Yeah,
never been readier.

161
00:08:00,416 --> 00:08:02,208
Just gotta keep
the team healthy.

162
00:08:02,291 --> 00:08:03,041
And you guys?

163
00:08:03,125 --> 00:08:04,375
He's freaking out,

164
00:08:04,458 --> 00:08:07,333
some days
a lot more than others.

165
00:08:07,416 --> 00:08:10,125
You can almost see the steam
shooting out of his ears.

166
00:08:11,500 --> 00:08:13,458
I think he might be
pushing himself too hard.

167
00:08:13,541 --> 00:08:17,541
He looked pretty dazed
between classes.

168
00:08:17,625 --> 00:08:19,875
I want him
to play the piano and all,

169
00:08:19,958 --> 00:08:23,208
but not if he's gotta suffer
the whole time.

170
00:08:24,500 --> 00:08:25,916
-You're right.
-[gasps]

171
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:27,250
He's suffering,

172
00:08:27,333 --> 00:08:29,750
but that pain is where
the music will come from.

173
00:08:30,958 --> 00:08:32,833
He's ripping off scabs

174
00:08:32,916 --> 00:08:35,666
and opening up old scars.

175
00:08:35,750 --> 00:08:38,125
That's the price
of admission.

176
00:08:38,208 --> 00:08:41,916
That's the way we can
make the music come to life.

177
00:08:42,833 --> 00:08:44,916
Arima's wrestling
with that.

178
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:46,166
I know it.

179
00:08:47,083 --> 00:08:48,208
-<i> And I don't...</i>

180
00:08:49,291 --> 00:08:51,416
Tell me something.

181
00:08:51,500 --> 00:08:52,916
How come you're so patient
with him

182
00:08:53,000 --> 00:08:54,625
through all of this?

183
00:08:54,708 --> 00:08:58,541
Hmm. I guess
I'd have to say it's 'cause...

184
00:09:01,166 --> 00:09:02,708
...he's kinda hopeless,

185
00:09:02,791 --> 00:09:03,666
like a little brother.

186
00:09:08,208 --> 00:09:10,916
He isn't hopeless.

187
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:13,000
He just doesn't know it yet.

188
00:09:16,041 --> 00:09:17,875
Good night.

189
00:09:17,958 --> 00:09:19,833
Yeah. See you tomorrow.

190
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:41,458
-[cellphone ringtone]
-Eh?

191
00:09:43,083 --> 00:09:44,208
Eh?

192
00:09:45,750 --> 00:09:47,083
Um, hey.

193
00:09:47,166 --> 00:09:48,208
I'm just walking home
from practice

194
00:09:48,291 --> 00:09:50,916
and thought I'd call you,
see what's up.

195
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:53,875
What a coincidence.
I'm walking home, too.

196
00:09:53,958 --> 00:09:55,291
It's like you and me are
on the same schedule lately.

197
00:09:55,375 --> 00:09:57,291
What's that about?

198
00:09:57,375 --> 00:09:58,791
[gasps]

199
00:09:58,875 --> 00:09:59,333
[crossing bell ringing]

200
00:09:59,416 --> 00:10:01,250
-<i> Tsubaki?</i>

201
00:10:02,833 --> 00:10:04,750
TSUBAKI:<i> In that "we,"</i>

202
00:10:04,833 --> 00:10:07,166
<i>there's no room for me.</i>

203
00:10:07,250 --> 00:10:09,000
-<i> Uh, you still there?</i>

204
00:10:09,083 --> 00:10:10,166
Hey, Saito...

205
00:10:10,250 --> 00:10:12,166
-<i> Yeah?</i>

206
00:10:12,750 --> 00:10:15,125
you wanna be...

207
00:10:15,208 --> 00:10:16,625
boyfriend and girlfriend?

208
00:10:16,708 --> 00:10:18,666
[train horn honks]

209
00:10:18,750 --> 00:10:20,833
["Etude Opus 25,
Number 5" playing]

210
00:10:23,125 --> 00:10:26,458
-KOUSEI:<i> Okay, still no idea</i>
<i>how I want to play this.</i>

211
00:10:26,541 --> 00:10:28,208
<i>Never mind why.</i>

212
00:10:28,291 --> 00:10:29,250
-KAORI: Milk break.

213
00:10:29,333 --> 00:10:30,333
Huh?

214
00:10:31,958 --> 00:10:33,625
<i>Who are you</i>
<i>doing this for, Kousei?</i>

215
00:10:35,666 --> 00:10:37,208
Let's call it a night
already.

216
00:10:37,291 --> 00:10:39,083
The moon is so bright.

217
00:10:39,166 --> 00:10:41,041
It doesn't even look real.

218
00:10:41,125 --> 00:10:43,000
I should keep going.

219
00:10:47,125 --> 00:10:47,875
Do you resent me?

220
00:10:47,958 --> 00:10:50,541
Huh?

221
00:10:50,625 --> 00:10:52,125
Tsubaki told me that

222
00:10:52,208 --> 00:10:54,416
this has been
kind of rough for you.

223
00:10:57,125 --> 00:10:58,458
Don't tell me it's not.

224
00:10:59,625 --> 00:11:02,375
When I saw your music room,
I knew it for sure.

225
00:11:02,458 --> 00:11:05,000
You can't hear the piano,

226
00:11:05,083 --> 00:11:06,583
so you've tried
to abandon it,

227
00:11:06,666 --> 00:11:09,625
but you want to play,
even now.

228
00:11:09,708 --> 00:11:12,833
You can't get rid of it
completely,

229
00:11:12,916 --> 00:11:16,000
so you hide it
under dust and clutter.

230
00:11:16,083 --> 00:11:18,250
You love it,
but can't go near it.

231
00:11:18,333 --> 00:11:20,875
You miss it,
but can't touch it.

232
00:11:20,958 --> 00:11:22,750
It tears you up.
I see that,

233
00:11:22,833 --> 00:11:27,291
no matter how much
I pretend not to.

234
00:11:27,375 --> 00:11:29,250
And all I do
is tell you junk like,

235
00:11:29,333 --> 00:11:31,458
"Let's go on a journey."

236
00:11:31,541 --> 00:11:34,583
You're hurting 'cause of me.

237
00:11:35,583 --> 00:11:37,291
I'm sorry.

238
00:11:37,375 --> 00:11:39,250
Please forgive me.

239
00:11:39,333 --> 00:11:41,375
[crying]

240
00:11:42,958 --> 00:11:47,375
Just don't forget who wiped
away that dust, all right?

241
00:11:48,333 --> 00:11:51,875
If I look pained,
it's 'cause--

242
00:11:51,958 --> 00:11:53,916
'cause adventures
can be kinda scary.

243
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:57,625
For me, it's like we've sailed
completely off the map.

244
00:11:59,708 --> 00:12:02,791
Creating something new
out of nothing is tough,

245
00:12:02,875 --> 00:12:06,541
but that's the part of it
that feeds your soul.

246
00:12:08,458 --> 00:12:12,458
KOUSEI:<i> Really, my world</i>
<i>had changed a long time ago.</i>

247
00:12:12,541 --> 00:12:14,583
<i>I just never realized it.</i>

248
00:12:15,875 --> 00:12:19,375
Guess my piano wasn't
the only one buried in the dust.

249
00:12:20,875 --> 00:12:20,916
Thank you.

250
00:12:22,375 --> 00:12:25,916
<i>Thank you for existing.</i>

251
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:29,375
<i>From the moment</i>
<i>I first laid eyes on you...</i>

252
00:12:30,416 --> 00:12:32,625
<i>life's been so colorful.</i>

253
00:12:34,750 --> 00:12:37,208
["Etude Opus 25,
Number 5" playing]

254
00:12:39,458 --> 00:12:40,958
You're a dummy.

255
00:12:43,791 --> 00:12:46,666
KOUSEI:<i> The girl</i>
<i>who likes my best friend,</i>

256
00:12:46,750 --> 00:12:49,375
<i>we're tucked away here</i>
<i>in the middle of the night,</i>

257
00:12:49,458 --> 00:12:52,666
<i>together as though</i>
<i>we're hiding from the moon...</i>

258
00:12:53,916 --> 00:12:56,375
<i>like we're</i>
<i>the last two people on Earth.</i>

259
00:12:58,250 --> 00:12:59,666
EMCEE:<i> All right, you guys,</i>

260
00:12:59,750 --> 00:13:02,583
<i>let's begin</i>
<i>our Regionals pep rally.</i>

261
00:13:02,666 --> 00:13:04,625
First we'll get some words
from our soccer captain.

262
00:13:04,708 --> 00:13:06,083
-[microphone feedback]
-Eh?

263
00:13:06,166 --> 00:13:08,333
WATARI:
Seriously, you guys are lucky.

264
00:13:08,416 --> 00:13:10,166
Want me to let you know why?

265
00:13:10,250 --> 00:13:12,166
'Cause you all know Watari,

266
00:13:12,250 --> 00:13:14,625
and after we win this thing,
I'm gonna be a star!

267
00:13:14,708 --> 00:13:15,541
[girls wailing]

268
00:13:15,625 --> 00:13:18,333
Number one, it's this guy!

269
00:13:18,416 --> 00:13:21,208
[laughs]
Come watch us, girls!

270
00:13:21,291 --> 00:13:24,041
I'll lead us
to our Watari-riffic destiny!

271
00:13:24,125 --> 00:13:25,708
[laughs]

272
00:13:25,791 --> 00:13:27,791
EMCEE: Uh, thank you
for that, soccer team.

273
00:13:31,208 --> 00:13:32,541
[tape player clicking]

274
00:13:32,625 --> 00:13:34,208
["Etude Opus 25,
Number 5" begins]

275
00:13:34,291 --> 00:13:36,333
[wails]

276
00:13:36,416 --> 00:13:37,458
Subpar.

277
00:13:37,541 --> 00:13:39,375
This is boring.

278
00:13:39,458 --> 00:13:41,708
Run-of-the-mill. Pedestrian.

279
00:13:41,791 --> 00:13:43,541
On the bright side,
you're playing all the notes,

280
00:13:43,625 --> 00:13:44,958
so there's that.

281
00:13:45,041 --> 00:13:47,541
Even if I'm
technically perfect,

282
00:13:47,625 --> 00:13:49,500
how does that help?

283
00:13:49,583 --> 00:13:50,875
Chopin's whispering to me.

284
00:13:50,958 --> 00:13:54,458
"Where are you
in all of this, Kousei"?

285
00:14:02,708 --> 00:14:03,750
Tell you what.

286
00:14:03,833 --> 00:14:05,791
Why don't we
go cheer on Tsubaki,

287
00:14:05,875 --> 00:14:08,250
you know,
get some fresh air?

288
00:14:08,333 --> 00:14:09,333
Won't do me any good.

289
00:14:09,416 --> 00:14:12,166
If I leave it like this,
I'll choke again.

290
00:14:12,250 --> 00:14:15,250
I can't let the sheet music
tie me down.

291
00:14:15,333 --> 00:14:17,083
I gotta break free.

292
00:14:17,166 --> 00:14:18,166
[grunts]

293
00:14:18,250 --> 00:14:20,083
You can do all that later.

294
00:14:21,791 --> 00:14:25,458
[laughs] Why sail the high seas
if you're stuck below-deck?

295
00:14:25,541 --> 00:14:28,458
Musicians need time to gaze
up at the sky now and then!

296
00:14:28,541 --> 00:14:29,416
[winces]

297
00:14:29,500 --> 00:14:31,500
[students cheering]

298
00:14:31,583 --> 00:14:34,708
-Yay!
-Do it!

299
00:14:35,541 --> 00:14:36,791
Last inning, you guys!

300
00:14:36,875 --> 00:14:38,666
Play smart defense,
and we got this!

301
00:14:38,750 --> 00:14:40,208
Time to work your magic.

302
00:14:40,291 --> 00:14:42,125
If we can't get a run in
by the end of the inning--

303
00:14:42,208 --> 00:14:43,166
Game over, I know.

304
00:14:43,250 --> 00:14:45,125
[gasps]

305
00:14:45,208 --> 00:14:47,000
-Do it!
-Hit it!

306
00:14:47,083 --> 00:14:49,291
Tsubaki,
aim for a window!

307
00:14:49,375 --> 00:14:50,791
Kousei.

308
00:14:50,875 --> 00:14:51,875
[gasps]

309
00:14:51,958 --> 00:14:53,708
[crowd noise fades]

310
00:14:56,208 --> 00:14:57,625
UMPIRE: Play ball!

311
00:14:57,708 --> 00:15:00,625
KAORI:<i> A famous violinist</i>
<i>once said,</i>

312
00:15:00,708 --> 00:15:02,583
<i>"Music's</i>
<i>the universal language."</i>

313
00:15:03,333 --> 00:15:05,291
Strike one!

314
00:15:05,375 --> 00:15:07,166
Tsubaki!

315
00:15:07,250 --> 00:15:09,458
<i>Weaving your notes</i>
<i>into another person's,</i>

316
00:15:09,541 --> 00:15:09,958
<i>you really get to know them.</i>

317
00:15:12,250 --> 00:15:13,833
-Ball!
-You're good, Tsubaki...

318
00:15:13,916 --> 00:15:16,625
-<i> It feels like</i>
<i>your hearts are connected,</i>

319
00:15:16,708 --> 00:15:19,500
<i>like your souls</i>
<i>are overlapping,</i>

320
00:15:19,583 --> 00:15:20,541
<i>instruments</i>
<i>harmonizing as one,</i>

321
00:15:20,625 --> 00:15:23,500
<i>it's just miraculous.</i>

322
00:15:23,583 --> 00:15:25,000
[metal bat rings]

323
00:15:25,083 --> 00:15:29,791
<i>In that moment,</i>
<i>there's nothing left to say.</i>

324
00:15:29,875 --> 00:15:31,458
TSUBAKI: Making me
lug him home like that!

325
00:15:31,541 --> 00:15:33,791
My shoulders felt like
they were gonna fall off!

326
00:15:33,875 --> 00:15:35,625
SAITO: Well, girls are bigger
at that age.

327
00:15:35,708 --> 00:15:36,833
It could have been
a lot worse.

328
00:15:36,916 --> 00:15:39,333
Hey, don't go using
man logic on me!

329
00:15:39,416 --> 00:15:41,291
It is the principle
of the thing.

330
00:15:42,541 --> 00:15:43,875
I tell you,
for as hopeless as he is,

331
00:15:43,958 --> 00:15:46,833
sit him at a piano,
and he's on fire.

332
00:15:46,916 --> 00:15:48,666
The crowd gave him
a standing ovation

333
00:15:48,750 --> 00:15:50,708
-the other day.
-[laughs]

334
00:15:50,791 --> 00:15:53,083
Huh? Did I say
something funny, or...

335
00:15:53,166 --> 00:15:54,250
No, nothing out
of the ordinary.

336
00:15:54,333 --> 00:15:57,791
You're always going on
about Arima. That's all.

337
00:15:58,458 --> 00:16:00,916
[students cheer]

338
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:02,250
You nailed it, Tsubaki!

339
00:16:02,333 --> 00:16:03,583
Yay! Attagirl!

340
00:16:03,666 --> 00:16:06,916
TSUBAKI:<i> I don't like this.</i>
<i>I don't like this.</i>

341
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:11,625
<i>And I know it's not my place</i>
<i>to feel all funky about it...</i>

342
00:16:11,708 --> 00:16:13,708
<i>but this isn't</i>
<i>a logical thing.</i>

343
00:16:13,791 --> 00:16:16,000
<i>I just don't like it.</i>

344
00:16:16,083 --> 00:16:16,708
<i>We were a team,</i>

345
00:16:16,791 --> 00:16:19,541
<i>Tsubaki and Kousei,</i>

346
00:16:19,625 --> 00:16:23,000
<i>through the laughter</i>
<i>and the tears.</i>

347
00:16:23,083 --> 00:16:27,166
<i>And now I'm</i>
<i>up in the nosebleed seats.</i>

348
00:16:27,250 --> 00:16:29,541
<i>I'm not there for him now,</i>

349
00:16:29,625 --> 00:16:31,416
<i>not the way she is.</i>

350
00:16:33,458 --> 00:16:34,916
-Tsubaki, no!
-Oh, no.

351
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:36,375
Go back to third!

352
00:16:36,458 --> 00:16:37,875
TSUBAKI:<i> I don't like this.</i>

353
00:16:37,958 --> 00:16:40,208
<i>Come on, Kousei.</i>
<i>Look at me, please.</i>

354
00:16:40,291 --> 00:16:43,000
<i>I'm right here.</i>
<i>I've been here the whole time.</i>

355
00:16:43,083 --> 00:16:43,208
[grunts]

356
00:16:49,750 --> 00:16:50,083
You're out of there!

357
00:16:52,750 --> 00:16:54,625
That's the game!

358
00:16:58,250 --> 00:17:00,250
[dog barking]

359
00:17:05,166 --> 00:17:06,791
Huh?

360
00:17:06,875 --> 00:17:09,416
Hey, I'm gonna
take this way home.

361
00:17:09,500 --> 00:17:11,916
[sighs]
But this one's shorter.

362
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:14,083
I don't wanna get between
you and your boyfriend.

363
00:17:14,166 --> 00:17:15,416
Huh?

364
00:17:15,500 --> 00:17:16,625
Boyfriend?

365
00:17:18,791 --> 00:17:19,083
Saito?

366
00:17:21,916 --> 00:17:23,500
No. Kousei.

367
00:17:24,666 --> 00:17:26,666
KOUSEI: Hey.

368
00:17:30,208 --> 00:17:30,666
[sighs]

369
00:17:30,750 --> 00:17:32,083
Hey, yourself.

370
00:17:38,583 --> 00:17:39,500
[shudders]

371
00:17:39,583 --> 00:17:42,916
[wails]

372
00:17:43,541 --> 00:17:45,958
Let me down.

373
00:17:46,041 --> 00:17:46,958
This is embarrassing.

374
00:17:47,041 --> 00:17:49,916
KOUSEI: No one's looking.
You're fine.

375
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:52,625
How'd you even know
that I hurt it?

376
00:17:52,708 --> 00:17:55,500
You do know we've been
friends for a while, right?

377
00:17:57,791 --> 00:17:59,833
So where's Kaori?

378
00:17:59,916 --> 00:18:01,291
She went home,

379
00:18:01,375 --> 00:18:03,666
told me I should
go find you by my lonesome.

380
00:18:03,750 --> 00:18:05,000
[gasps]

381
00:18:05,083 --> 00:18:06,583
After that tumble
down the hill,

382
00:18:06,666 --> 00:18:08,250
you carried me home
just like this,

383
00:18:08,333 --> 00:18:09,833
even though you were hurt,
too.

384
00:18:09,916 --> 00:18:11,000
You remember, right?

385
00:18:11,083 --> 00:18:12,208
Your own ankle swelled up

386
00:18:12,291 --> 00:18:14,125
to what looked
like a basketball.

387
00:18:14,208 --> 00:18:16,333
I forgot about that.

388
00:18:16,416 --> 00:18:19,958
You're the same old Tsubaki
you were back in the day.

389
00:18:20,041 --> 00:18:21,375
No, I'm not.

390
00:18:22,708 --> 00:18:25,250
TSUBAKI:
<i>My heart is so up in the air.</i>

391
00:18:25,333 --> 00:18:28,000
Nice try,
but I know better than that.

392
00:18:28,083 --> 00:18:31,708
The point is you never have
to hold back with me, okay?

393
00:18:31,791 --> 00:18:32,291
[sighs]

394
00:18:34,375 --> 00:18:35,666
Over the years,

395
00:18:35,750 --> 00:18:38,291
you've always had to worry
about me so much.

396
00:18:38,375 --> 00:18:41,625
Maybe you should let me
worry about you for a change.

397
00:18:41,708 --> 00:18:44,250
I might just be
the flaky kid brother to you,

398
00:18:44,333 --> 00:18:46,666
but I'll try hard.

399
00:18:46,750 --> 00:18:48,083
I'll give it my all,

400
00:18:48,166 --> 00:18:51,250
because I think that you
deserve to be happy.

401
00:18:53,166 --> 00:18:55,125
After all,
I can't hitch a ride

402
00:18:55,208 --> 00:18:56,958
on your shoulders forever.

403
00:18:57,958 --> 00:18:59,958
-[sighs]
-Speaking of that,

404
00:19:00,041 --> 00:19:02,000
you're a lot lighter up there
than I thought you'd be.

405
00:19:02,083 --> 00:19:04,333
I guess you're a girl
after all, huh?

406
00:19:06,625 --> 00:19:08,125
Ugh! Better a girl
than a weirdo!

407
00:19:08,208 --> 00:19:10,250
That was a weird thing to say.
I'm sorry.

408
00:19:12,541 --> 00:19:15,958
I guess there's
just something in the air.

409
00:19:19,291 --> 00:19:23,291
TSUBAKI:<i> Who cares about music</i>
<i>or even words?</i>

410
00:19:23,375 --> 00:19:26,166
<i>Kousei and I, we've spent</i>
<i>more time together</i>

411
00:19:26,250 --> 00:19:28,083
<i>than I could ever count,</i>

412
00:19:28,166 --> 00:19:30,916
<i>so many precious memories</i>
<i>that are just ours.</i>

413
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:33,583
-<i> You know what?</i>

414
00:19:33,666 --> 00:19:36,791
<i>Next time, I'll give you</i>
<i>a piggyback ride, okay?</i>

415
00:19:37,833 --> 00:19:39,958
TSUBAKI: [crying]

416
00:19:40,875 --> 00:19:42,250
We came so far,

417
00:19:42,333 --> 00:19:46,750
but we lost today,
and it's all my fault!

418
00:19:49,000 --> 00:19:51,416
The team fought
so hard for this,

419
00:19:51,500 --> 00:19:55,416
and I ruined it!
I ruined it for everyone!

420
00:19:55,916 --> 00:19:58,125
[sobbing]

421
00:19:58,208 --> 00:20:00,083
TSUBAKI:
<i>I'm torn up over the loss...</i>

422
00:20:00,166 --> 00:20:01,083
<i>crushed, really.</i>

423
00:20:01,166 --> 00:20:03,416
I was stupid
and went for broke!

424
00:20:03,500 --> 00:20:04,583
<i>My ankle hurts,</i>

425
00:20:04,666 --> 00:20:07,750
<i>and my eyes</i>
<i>are filled with tears.</i>

426
00:20:07,833 --> 00:20:10,458
-[sobbing]
<i>-Never felt worse.</i>

427
00:20:10,541 --> 00:20:14,333
<i>So why are the stars</i>
<i>sparkling so brightly?</i>

428
00:20:16,375 --> 00:20:18,291
<i>His hair smells</i>
<i>like the music room,</i>

429
00:20:18,375 --> 00:20:22,500
<i>and I can hear</i>
<i>the rasp of his breath.</i>

430
00:20:22,583 --> 00:20:24,208
<i>He's so warm beneath my tears.</i>

431
00:20:26,125 --> 00:20:28,375
<i>I-It's us again.</i>

432
00:20:28,458 --> 00:20:32,666
<i>I just wish time</i>
<i>would stand still for me.</i>

433
00:20:39,708 --> 00:20:41,666
TAKESHI:
Okay, I give up. What is it?

434
00:20:41,750 --> 00:20:44,000
This is the list
of the Maihou contestants.

435
00:20:44,083 --> 00:20:45,041
Check out the name
that I flagged.

436
00:20:45,125 --> 00:20:47,583
What do you think of that?

437
00:20:47,666 --> 00:20:49,333
-[breathing heavily]
-[gasps]

438
00:20:49,416 --> 00:20:52,500
Two years,
I've been waiting for this.

439
00:20:52,583 --> 00:20:54,166
<i>Finally some revenge</i>

440
00:20:54,250 --> 00:20:56,666
<i>for all those years</i>
<i>of being one-upped.</i>

441
00:20:56,750 --> 00:20:58,916
[playing "Winter Wind"]

442
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:00,416
YURIKO:
I take it you've heard, then?

443
00:21:00,500 --> 00:21:01,166
EMI: What are you
talking about?

444
00:21:01,250 --> 00:21:03,791
Right, like you don't know.

445
00:21:03,875 --> 00:21:04,833
Look at how you're playing.

446
00:21:04,916 --> 00:21:07,000
It's all in your head.

447
00:21:07,083 --> 00:21:08,125
[chuckles]

448
00:21:09,583 --> 00:21:10,791
EMI:<i> After all</i>
<i>my wondering and waiting,</i>

449
00:21:10,875 --> 00:21:14,000
<i>you simply appear</i>

450
00:21:14,083 --> 00:21:17,125
<i>just in time for me to wipe up</i>
<i>the floor with you...</i>

451
00:21:17,958 --> 00:21:19,458
<i>Kousei Arima.</i>

452
00:21:22,750 --> 00:21:25,666
["Kirameki" playing]

453
00:21:25,750 --> 00:21:27,666
[singing in Japanese]

